They're written in Objective-C and C# respectively: two languages, and specifically, two languages other than Appium's core language. Because of this they lag behind the Appium server and are often broken."

1 [2016-12-16T07:03:49] <pramodnaik> Divya-tfw: : First u have to collect all the contacts in an ArrayList. and compare if that array list is sorted.
2 [2016-12-16T07:04:11] <pramodnaik> Divya-tfw: : Example for checking sortedboolean checkSorting(ArrayList< String > arraylist){boolean isSorted=true;for(int i=1;i < arraylist.size();i++){if(arraylist.get(i-1).compareTo(arraylist.get(i)) > 0){isSorted= false;break;}}return isSorted;}

1 [2016-12-28T13:04:37] <shabinmohan> @prabudakshan this is working for mepublic void scroll(String TypeOfScroll) {Dimension size = driver.manage().window().getSize();int y_start = (int) (size.height * 0.60);int y_end = (int) (size.height * 0.30);int x = size.width / 2;if (TypeOfScroll.equals("up")){driver.swipe(x, y_start,x, y_end, 4000);}else if (TypeOfScroll.equals("down")){driver.swipe(x, y_end, x, y_start, 4000);}else{System.out.println("Please specify the type of scroll");}}

1 [2017-01-16T15:15:41] <hazmeister> the appium server receives instructions set as POST and GET commands
2 [2017-01-16T15:15:48] <hazmeister> they can be sent from any language
3 [2017-01-16T15:17:40] <rajakarthikeya> which part/device converts java/C# code to Http
4 [2017-01-16T15:17:53] <rajakarthikeya> hazmeister:
5 [2017-01-16T15:19:53] <hazmeister> you have three parts: the device, appium server and your local language bindings
6 [2017-01-16T15:20:12] <hazmeister> you write java code that makes requests to the appium server as POST or GET
7 [2017-01-16T15:20:40] <hazmeister> the appium server understands the instructions and sends to them using the native automation technology for the device
8 [2017-01-16T15:20:48] <hazmeister> e.g. XCUITest for iOS
9 [2017-01-16T15:22:13] <hazmeister> or UIAutomator for Android
10 [2017-01-16T15:32:06] <rajakarthikeya> Thanks@hazmeister

4 [2017-01-29T20:44:21] <hardik-d> appium has a newCommandTimeout capability

6 [2017-01-29T20:44:45] <hardik-d> you can increase that to your liking

8 [2017-01-29T20:45:48] <hardik-d> like wait(5) {@driver.find_element(:accessibility_id, "OK").click }
9 [2017-01-29T20:45:55] <hardik-d> 5 is in seconds
10 [2017-01-29T20:47:00] <hardik-d> there is also a wait_true method which you can use for a condition to be true

1 [2017-03-10T12:49:57] <argeas> hi all ... is there a way to tell appium to update the apk rather than installing the apk and clearing data
2 [2017-03-10T13:16:01] <argeas> you can either go adb install test.apk
3 [2017-03-10T13:16:13] <argeas> where it will only install if the apk is a newer version
4 [2017-03-10T13:16:28] <argeas> and you will not lose settings i.e. u wont need to relogin
5 [2017-03-10T13:16:39] <argeas> or you can go adb install -r .apk
6 [2017-03-10T13:16:55] <argeas> where it forces install... and u lose defaults...  and u have to relogin..
7 [2017-03-10T13:17:05] <argeas> appium does -r by default..

10 [2017-03-27T21:46:59] <rajivd15> here are the steps - appium versions(apium1.6.X server and appium1.5.3 GUI).launch the appium (1.6 or above) from the command prompt/terminalOpen the appium 1.5.3 GUI and fill in all required settings(AppPath, package, Automation Name, Platform version - even if we couldn't find in drop down edit it, Device Name) DONOT HIT LAUNCHthen click on the inspector icon on the GUI.This should open appium inspector using Appium server.

4 [2017-03-28T13:28:18] <coding-yogi> If u put under etc it is system wide

6 [2017-03-28T13:28:37] <coding-yogi> It's only for that user

7 [2017-04-14T09:41:52] <coding-yogi> A problem
8 [2017-04-14T09:42:04] <coding-yogi> It's terminating the string
9 [2017-04-14T09:44:05] <coding-yogi> Generally when we use xpaths in JavaScript for web there is no escape character
10 [2017-04-14T09:44:18] <coding-yogi> So ' is replaced by "
11 [2017-04-14T09:44:27] <coding-yogi> Sorry
12 [2017-04-14T09:44:44] <coding-yogi> Gitter is converting text to "
13 [2017-04-14T09:44:53] <coding-yogi> & quot ;
14 [2017-04-14T09:45:02] <coding-yogi> Above string without spaces
15 [2017-04-14T09:48:22] <john74590009_twitter> U meandriver.findElement(By.xpath("//android.widget.RelativeLayout/android.widget.TextView[contains(@text,"Today's Deals")]")).click();

17 [2017-04-14T09:51:07] <coding-yogi> Replace ' by &quot; (without underscore)

5 [2017-05-02T12:07:29] <NaveenThiyagarajan> like preceding and following sibling

1 [2017-05-12T08:52:28] <priyankshah217> there are possibility, since in some case UIAUtomator2 server takes time shutdown hence there may be a chance that next appium test might fail due to unable to start instrument
2 [2017-05-12T08:53:07] <priyankshah217> we faced similar situation.. so we explicitly shutdown UIAutomator2 Server
3 [2017-05-12T08:54:10] <priyankshah217> i dont know that whether its been taken care in java-client but being on safer side and making tests more reliable we explicitly cleanup uiautomar2

22 [2017-05-18T14:54:53] <NaveenThiyagarajan> I used to get the timeout issue...only  if the appium is already processing an request and if it taking time ...then your IOS inspector request will go into queue ... OR .. for some reason there is an request that got struck(mean no response sent back) on appium side then ...it might not process the next upcoming requests... So try restarting the appium server and make sure the appium server completed processing your earlier requests before launching appium inspector

1 [2017-06-02T13:35:31] <coding-yogi> TSangani: , I think moveTo is relative from current position
2 [2017-06-02T13:36:17] <coding-yogi> Your X is 1100 and you are moving to 56, so final coordinate is 1156
3 [2017-06-02T13:36:39] <coding-yogi> if its exceeding resolution of your device, it will fail
4 [2017-06-02T13:37:10] <coding-yogi> if thats what you are trying for Left swipe, you should be using negative values
5 [2017-06-02T13:37:19] <coding-yogi> -56 instead of 56
6 [2017-06-02T13:37:57] <coding-yogi> or if 56 is your target pixel, you should move -1044
7 [2017-06-02T13:38:08] <coding-yogi> Swipe is deprecated
8 [2017-06-02T13:38:20] <coding-yogi> not recommended to use swipe

2 [2017-07-12T08:49:34] <mgmanikandan87> org.openqa.selenium.StaleElementReferenceException:
3 [2017-07-12T08:49:44] <mgmanikandan87> this is because
4 [2017-07-12T08:50:00] <mgmanikandan87> you get the element first
5 [2017-07-12T08:50:23] <mgmanikandan87> after the UI get changed
6 [2017-07-12T08:50:35] <mgmanikandan87> then your are trying to click that element
7 [2017-07-12T08:51:05] <mgmanikandan87> or any action on that element
8 [2017-07-12T08:51:36] <mgmanikandan87> this will happen most of the list element logic with loop condition
9 [2017-07-12T08:52:10] <mgmanikandan87> before the loop your getting the element
10 [2017-07-12T08:52:18] <mgmanikandan87> then do some action inside lopp
11 [2017-07-12T08:52:34] <mgmanikandan87> then loop will continous for next set
12 [2017-07-12T08:52:40] <mgmanikandan87> that time it will fail

1 [2017-07-13T14:58:57] <ssskkprd> public void performScrollTillElementAndClick(AppiumDriver driver, List<MobileElement> element) throws InterruptedException {        boolean foundElement = false;        try {            if(element == null || element.isEmpty()) {                do {                    performScroll(driver);                    Thread.sleep(2000);                    if(element.size() > 0) { foundElement = true; break; }                    } while(foundElement);            }        } catch(NoSuchElementException e) {}        if(foundElement) element.get(0).click();    }-- sample which worked for me -- here you can pass direction n based on direction - relevant things can be performed in performScroll function

20 [2017-07-25T04:26:18] <Rohithnm> GeeChao: yes
21 [2017-07-25T04:27:00] <Rohithnm> GeeChao: i need to have common code base with single test scripts for both iOS and Android
22 [2017-07-25T04:29:46] <Rohithnm> GeeChao: is it possible??
23 [2017-07-25T04:29:57] <Rohithnm> is there is any hurdle ?
24 [2017-07-25T04:31:35] <priyankshah217> You can have common code for android and ios.. provided ur user journey and UI interaction are same..
25 [2017-07-25T04:33:09] <priyankshah217> also it would be tricky to maintain.. you need to excessivly use@AndroidFindByand@IOSFindByfor UI elements to ur page objects (otherwise ur ended up with lots of if else blocks :) ) now its up to u how efficiently u implement it
26 [2017-07-25T04:36:16] <Rohithnm> Have you tried it??@priyankshah217
27 [2017-07-25T04:36:25] <priyankshah217> yep
28 [2017-07-25T04:37:25] <Rohithnm> cool.... so u r using single code base for both ?? and its working fine??
29 [2017-07-25T04:39:08] <priyankshah217> yes.. but it depends on u.. but before that u have supportive UI..
30 [2017-07-25T04:39:51] <priyankshah217> if android and ios app have different user path, then there is no sense to share common code abse
31 [2017-07-25T04:40:12] <priyankshah217> before jumping into that, just ensure that first
32 [2017-07-25T04:40:41] <Rohithnm> UI is common for both iOS and Android

3 [2017-07-25T06:01:31] <priyankshah217> GeeChao: , how can u validate UI controls.. because locator stratergies are different on both platforms.. and obviously this kind of implementation has to be done on page level.. not step definitions level..

1 [2017-07-25T05:55:14] <GeeChao> Rohithnm: yep what@priyankshah217said is spot on, if the user workflow/journey on the screens is different for ios/android there is no point sharing it
2 [2017-07-25T05:55:55] <GeeChao> However I recommend for you to look into a state machine design pattern to assist you in implementing your solution
3 [2017-07-25T05:56:43] <GeeChao> Where your test framework will know which os type you're executing on, and decide which class/method to use automatically
4 [2017-07-25T05:57:13] <GeeChao> So you do not need to implement your if/else logic in all of your step definitions etc.
5 [2017-07-25T06:12:45] <Rohithnm> GeeChao: Thanks for the suggestion
6 [2017-07-25T07:07:46] <GeeChao> priyankshah217: I'm not sure if you understand what I meant. If you implement the state machine design pattern into your tests, and set the context at the beginning of your tests depending on if it's IOS or Android - Your tests will know which OS it is operating on
7 [2017-07-25T07:09:00] <GeeChao> From here, your step definitions will just call your pageobject.doMethod(). For example, you will have 2 LoginPages, LoginPageIOS.Java and LoginPageAndroid.Java
8 [2017-07-25T07:09:49] <GeeChao> However in your step definitions, you will NOT need to specifically call, if(ios) { loginPageIOS.doMethod() } else { loginPageAndroid.doMethod() }
9 [2017-07-25T07:10:11] <GeeChao> Your test framework will already know which class to call based on the context set
10 [2017-07-25T07:19:05] <GeeChao> Furthermore, something you should also check out is something called the screenplay/journey pattern, page objects are not necessarily the best domain models to apply if you want to follow SOLID development principles
11 [2017-07-25T07:20:30] <GeeChao> It's good practice to even separate your element locators from your "page object methods", so that your classes have single responsibility
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

7 [2017-08-03T09:43:16] <Neni2016_twitter> Usually in POM, we maintain the classes as per pages. in this if pages are more classes may be more, instead of this why can't we maintain the set of few classes in form of methods to cover all the functionalities of all the pages and call those methods from your tests, in this way we can reduce the number of classes and we can remember even the classes too since we have few, why we wont prefer this way ???
8 [2017-08-03T09:44:49] <siggerzz> Neni2016_twitter: You got to think of people working on it in the future. It's easier to maintain if you have the methods for a specific page in a class dedicated to that page
9 [2017-08-03T09:49:46] <Neni2016_twitter> siggerzz: , yes it may be crt but there is chance to have some common functionalities in more than one page assume with same id/name, in this case in POM we will write a function in all the pages to handle it, here we are missing the reuseability , is not it
10 [2017-08-03T09:50:09] <siggerzz> You can use a 'BasePage' class
11 [2017-08-03T09:50:15] <siggerzz> and have your pages inherit it
12 [2017-08-03T09:50:47] <siggerzz> Then just declare all the common functionality in the BaseClass and call the method in the pages that need it
13 [2017-08-03T09:51:10] <siggerzz> Neni2016_twitter:
14 [2017-08-03T09:53:26] <Neni2016_twitter> siggerzz: yes got it, thanks for clarification

1 [2017-09-05T12:08:26] <gczudowski> I can tell you how I did it in javascript @davidmorrison1981 . there are two solutions to your problemoneyou can go to xcuitestdriver project and add proper certificate manually to WebDriverAgent.xcodeproj using xcodetwoyou can automate the process by creating an xcode.conf file, with the following content:DEVELOPMENT_TEAM = <here you put development team id>CODE_SIGN_IDENTITY = iPhone Developerand only put the team id, the rest you leave as it is

1 [2017-10-02T11:37:27] <astaninama> Hello. Please tell me. Is Appium a driver or wrapper over Selenium? Does it contain own WebDriver? Thanks
2 [2017-10-02T11:51:12] <mgmanikandan87> astaninama: yes it is
3 [2017-10-02T11:52:12] <astaninama> mgmanikandan87: Is it driver or wrapper?
4 [2017-10-02T11:52:21] <mgmanikandan87> wrapper
5 [2017-10-02T11:52:35] <Asimk21> astaninama: You are correct. Appium is not a wrapper over Selenium. It uses JSONWire protocol used in Selenium. Appium has its own implementation to communicate with target. The main intention of using JSONWire protocol is to have similarity between desktop web and mobile.
6 [2017-10-02T11:58:23] <Asimk21> Why do you need wrapper over appium?
7 [2017-10-02T12:01:36] <Asimk21> Sorry, I didn't get your question. What do you want to know?
8 [2017-10-02T12:06:03] <Asimk21> If you are using appium directly, then "no" there are no wrappers over it. But if you consider any cloud specific solution then they might have wrapper over appium.
9 [2017-10-02T12:06:55] <Asimk21> TuHuynhVan: There is nothing pictorial I know of but here is what you can refer [<-LINK->]
10 [2017-10-02T12:09:56] <Asimk21> TuHuynhVan: Cheers.
11 [2017-10-02T12:10:40] <Asimk21> astaninama: One more thing, Appium Desktop is wrapper over appium server.
12 [2017-10-02T12:12:12] <mgmanikandan87> TuHuynhVan: this might give some knowledge appium
13 [2017-10-02T12:12:12] <mgmanikandan87>  [<-LINK->]
14 [2017-10-02T12:23:07] <mgmanikandan87> astaninama: for more information just through this [<-LINK->]
15 [2017-10-02T13:16:46] <Asimk21> astaninama: Appium will help execute tests. It will install client on device which polls appium server for test commands.
16 [2017-10-04T07:49:12] <Asimk21> Appium uses UIAutomator and Selendroid to communicate with devices.
17 [2017-10-04T07:49:48] <Asimk21> Appium is kind of wrapper for UIAutomator and Selendroid.

1 [2017-10-13T09:10:36] <SandeepTekslate_twitter> Should I use Appium or Robotium for test automation?                                                                                                                                          I was in your shoes about 2 years ago and chose Appium (https://goo.gl/7jd77F) (over other competing frameworks including robotium)Appium has a strong community - look at their github activity and the volume of email on appium discuss.They are supported by a strong company - saucelabs. Who also do a lot of work on seleniumThey don't modify the app under test - this is not a biggie factor for me but its nice to know that your app in production is the exact same app you tested.Your automation will be able to support iOS - with reasonable effort.Client libraries can be in any langauge so no need to write boring Java codeIn these two years things have improved further onAppium does a lot of effort to support each version of iOS and AndroidThey started doing strong tutorials Mobile App Automation Made Awesome, appium-bootcamp etc.They started doing an official mobile selenium spec - spec-draft.md - selenium - Browser automation frameworkUsing saucelabs I was able to trigger parallel test runsSound support for webview automation. Now you can reuse your existing webview automation and have 2 drivers in one test framework

1 [2017-10-25T00:27:43] <GeeChao> hey@Rup1I went through the same thing a while back on automating a native-ios app in nodeJS
2 [2017-10-25T00:28:55] <GeeChao> The documentation is basically non-existant because it's all so poorly documented
3 [2017-10-25T00:29:29] <GeeChao> But basically from my PoCs I couldn't get the native selenium webdriver to work at all with appium, the only 2 libraries that supported it were wd.js and webdriverio.js
4 [2017-10-25T00:30:15] <GeeChao> I opted for WDIO because it was a lot more fluent, and it also had its own testrunner which handled the asynchronous browser API, ensuring that all your webdriver commands were synchronous and executed one after another

1 [2017-12-29T11:31:44] <siva4862> HI Guys, I have a button on android mobile, called "READ MORE" if we click on that it will go to a page where the whole new will load. But how to verify whether its loaded or not ?
2 [2017-12-29T11:32:24] <siva4862> *new = news
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1 [2017-12-29T12:50:49] <ghost~5a393e57d73408ce4f8409f5> siva4862: Does the News page which will load after clicking have a "READ MORE" element anywhere? If it doesn't, after clicking this element on the previous page, check if this element still exists. If it does, it means you're still on the same page. You may also check if any element which certainly exists only on the News page is visible. In other words: if after clicking, "READ MORE" is not visible and a News element is visible, the page loaded successfully. This is one solution, hope it helps
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

1 [2018-03-27T08:20:35] <majdukovic> sitansu_kar007_twitter: I think what you are looking for is singleton. You create only one instance of the driver for all test cases, so if you have 2 test cases (login and logout test case), first test case will get you logged in and after this test case is finished you will stay logged in, logout test case starts from where first one finished, so you are still logged in, you just need to logout in second test case. Note that this way you can't run logout test case without login test case, test cases will be dependent on each other (at least in this case). Here is how I do it in Python, not sure which client you use: [<-CODE->]

2 [2018-03-30T07:54:05] <majdukovic> @pattraynor as @mgmanikandan87 already mentioned, we are unsure if you want to launch browser on the mobile phone or you want to launch app? If you want to launch the app then you don't need anything related to browser (i.e. url, browser name, etc.) and you need to change path to your app, instead of pointing to the .ipa you need to point to the .app file (check thishttps://stackoverflow.com/questions/2949916/what-is-different-betwen-ipa-and-app-format-in-using-iphone)If you want to launch browser on the mobile then you don't need app path, bundle id, app name, etc.To know more abut capabilities, check this: https://appium.io/docs/en/writing-running-appium/caps/

1 [2018-04-05T09:02:44] <Gamaiva> @SukeshBolar   try this......public void scrollIos(String move, IOSDriver<?> drive) throws InterruptedException {        RemoteWebElement element = (RemoteWebElement) drive.findElement(By.xpath("//XCUIElementTypeTable"));        String elementID = element.getId();        HashMap<String, String> scrollObject = new HashMap<String, String>();        scrollObject.put("element", elementID); // Only for ‘scroll in element’        scrollObject.put("direction", move);        drive.executeScript("mobile:scroll", scrollObject);        Thread.sleep(1000);    }

1 [2018-05-15T08:26:54] <Asimk21> Espresso is for Android only, XCTests for IOS only, Appium is for both.
2 [2018-05-15T08:28:24] <majdukovic> Hermi09: espresso and XCUITests aremainlyfor developers (unit tests, white box testing), because you need to know the code structure and how the code works.Appium is for testers (black box testing), where you don't know the code structure, you just provide input and expect certain output.
3 [2018-05-15T08:55:40] <priyankshah217> if you want to run your automation with existing dev code, then use xcui or espresso.. because u can configure build pipeline to run these tests
4 [2018-05-15T09:02:01] <majdukovic> I think appium would suit you better because you have app for iOS and Android, so you can write same tests for both platforms in one language of choice (Java, Ruby, JS, Python etc.) your team is most comfortable with.And although appium is a lot slower than espresso or xcuitest (because with appium you need to send command to server and than wait for the response, with espresso/xcuitest tests are executed within app), you can test in parallel so suite execution willideallylast as the longest test case in test suite.
5 [2018-05-15T11:40:16] <sitansu_kar007_twitter> These two function works on Appium 1.7.1driver.release();driver.perform();On iOS platform?For me, it works on Android but not on the iOSCan anyone help me out!Thanks

5 [2018-08-21T09:19:48] <sumitbera> WebDriverWait wait = new WebDriverWait(driver, 10);        WebElement element = wait.until(ExpectedConditions.visibilityOf(By.id("mention locator value")));The wait should look like this where driver will wait for 10 seconds till your element is not visible. You can also increase the time as per your need. Place this statement before you statement of clicking on "search box ideal text"

1 [2018-08-21T09:41:48] <sumitbera> MasoomaFatima: Welcome, hope it worked for you
2 [2018-08-23T08:33:49] <sumitbera> vemuvpk_twitter: Seems like you are trying to switch between NATIVE to WEB and vice-versa. You can use appium getContextHandle. Which will look something like below:Switch to WEB_VIEW:public static void switchToWebView(AppiumDriver driver) {Set<String> allContext = driver.getContextHandles();for (String context : allContext) {if (context.contains("WEBVIEW"))driver.context(context);}}Switch to NATIVE_VIEW:public static void switchBackToNativeAppiumDriver driver) {Set<String> contextNames = driver.getContextHandles();for (String contextName : contextNames) {if (contextName.contains("NATIVE"))driver.context(contextName);}}
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

10 [2018-08-30T20:08:03] <Edge-Man> Kavetipreetamkumar: : here you go: public static void swipeHorizontal(AppiumDriver driver, double startPercentage, double finalPercentage, double anchorPercentage, int duration) throws Exception {Dimension size = driver.manage().window().getSize();int anchor = (int) (size.heightanchorPercentage);        int startPoint = (int) (size.widthstartPercentage);int endPoint = (int) (size.width * finalPercentage);new TouchAction(driver).press(startPoint, anchor).waitAction(Duration.ofMillis(duration)).moveTo(endPoint, anchor).release().perform();} [<-CODE->]

3 [2018-08-31T12:59:45] <LyubomirStoimchev> Because I don't think that AndroidDriver has implemented javascript execution
4 [2018-08-31T13:00:20] <LyubomirStoimchev> And also you cannot use the code that you mentioned to scroll in android native elements
5 [2018-08-31T13:01:11] <LyubomirStoimchev> javascript can be used when you are working with webviews
6 [2018-08-31T13:03:07] <LyubomirStoimchev> the way I did is to scroll and compare the objects that were visible before the scroll and after the scroll - this way I will know if I have reached the end of the list

9 [2018-08-31T13:04:17] <LyubomirStoimchev> yep, read my last comment
10 [2018-08-31T13:06:15] <LyubomirStoimchev> Also just a quick tip - you cannot compare elements directly because every time they will have different ids. Instead you should compare their properties
11 [2018-08-31T13:07:33] <LyubomirStoimchev> so it's something like this: get all visible elements -> scroll -> get all new visible elements -> compare old and new elements
12 [2018-08-31T13:15:51] <sunilpatro1985> My question is how to scroll the list box, if I can scroll, I will be able to get whole list.
13 [2018-08-31T13:30:55] <LyubomirStoimchev> You have to use TouchAction. See the code that@Edge-Manposted.
14 [2018-08-31T13:33:53] <LyubomirStoimchev> I'm currently using this:/// <summary>/// Swipe between elements/// </summary>/// <param name="fromElement">Scroll from element location</param>/// <param name="toElement">Scroll to element location</param>public override void Swipe(IWebElement fromElement, IWebElement toElement){new TouchAction(NativeDriver).LongPress(fromElement.Location.X, fromElement.Location.Y).MoveTo(toElement.Location.X, toElement.Location.Y).Release().Perform();}
15 [2018-08-31T13:40:19] <sunilpatro1985> LyubomirStoimchev: Great, it worked, I thought press and move to is for screen and might not applicable for a dropdown list,Here is the updated code for latest appium version > 6.0 [<-CODE->]
16 [2018-08-31T13:51:24] <LyubomirStoimchev> yep it will work, although I'm a fan of magic numbers(those 0.5 and 0.2 values)
17 [2018-08-31T13:54:55] <LyubomirStoimchev> If you have top and bottom navigation bars in the application those values might fuck up things because you have to get scrolling coordinates based on the view between top and bottom bar and not coordinates of the whole screen

1 [2019-01-04T05:49:52] <rajeshchy> cloud74624: where did you see that desired capabilities are deprecated?
2 [2019-01-04T08:37:47] <LyubomirStoimchev> cloud74624: I have the same problem. It is caused by the latest versions of WD where if the session is W3C specification complaint then all find methods are converted into CSS. This means that even if you try to find the element by ID then WD converts the ID into CSS(and CSS is not supported for native elements). If you are using Java client you can try adding the capability 'forceMjsonwp = true'. Unfortunately that capability doesn't work on dotnet client(you have to fork appium -> remove W3C capabilities in session creation method -> run it locally).
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

3 [2019-01-10T08:24:26] <suheel1> For more clear defines:Problem: [<-CODE->] What i have done so far: [<-CODE->] What is feel is,its not able to find the element on web view,do we need to switch from mobile view to web view?If so , how to do it?
4 [2019-01-10T15:41:02] <suheel1> Yes,@LyubomirStoimchev, when I before clicking the action button I was in web context only after that url launched in Mobile's chrome browser where driver.context is failing and
5 [2019-01-10T15:41:46] <suheel1> WebView.setWebContentsDebuggingEnabled(true) added in desired capability
6 [2019-01-10T15:44:01] <suheel1> Your help is appreciated
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1 [2019-01-10T14:29:31] <LyubomirStoimchev> suheel1: To interact with web elements, you first have to switch from native context to web context. To do so user Driver.Context(webContext). If the url is opened in a webview (for android) you will have to add this code "WebView.setWebContentsDebuggingEnabled(true)" and then recompile the app. Also for android you need to also have the proper chromedriver when interacting with web elements.
2 [2019-01-11T10:51:08] <LyubomirStoimchev> suheel1: WebView.setWebContentsDebuggingEnabled(true)  is not set in the desired capabilities. It has to be added into the source code of the app itself and then recompile the app.About the context, if it's an external browser that opens then you have to switch the context AFTER the browser is opened(if you do it before you won't be able to find the webcontext).
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

1 [2019-05-17T10:09:42] <wswebcreation> Appium gets back the complete UI-hierarchy of an app (compared to the DOM on web) Android (UiAutomator2) only gives back the elements that are in the view (so not the elements that are shown after swiping for example). This makes Android already faster in comparison to iOSNeeds to beAppium gets back the complete UI-hierarchy of an app (compared to the DOM on web) for iOS. Android (UiAutomator2) only gives back the elements that are in the view (so not the elements that are shown after swiping for example). This makes Android already faster in comparison to iOS

Please find the below code.DesiredCapabilities desiredCapabilities = new DesiredCapabilities();desiredCapabilities.setCapability(“automationName”, “XCUITest”);desiredCapabilities.setCapability(“platformName”, “iOS”);desiredCapabilities.setCapability(“platformVersion”, version);desiredCapabilities.setCapability(“deviceName”, deviceName);desiredCapabilities.setCapability(“udid”, deviceName);desiredCapabilities.setCapability(“orientation”, “LANDSCAPE”);Video Recording Code:((CanRecordScreen) driver.getAppiumDriver()).startRecordingScreen();try{String video = ((CanRecordScreen) driver.getAppiumDriver()).stopRecordingScreen();byte[] decodedVideo = Base64.getMimeDecoder().decode(video); [<-CODE->]

1 [2019-09-21T20:33:47] <sitansu_kar007_twitter> balaji-sachidanandam: Just for an overview: in appium you can use absolute xpath, accessibility id and xpath.Using appium inspector or Xcode accessibility inspector you can determinexpath: //XCUIElementTypeStaticText[@label=''];Accesssinlity id: use directly.XPATH: driver.findElement(by.xpath(//XCUIElementTypeStaticText[@label='XYZ']));Access id: driver.findElement(MobileBy.id("XYZ"))And try to avoild absolute xapth!

1 [2019-10-31T10:42:54] <srinu-kodi> testopc1: If you say locators are changes, what are those locators. Are they classNames of the locator ? If you are using the class names as locators, then you should avoid using them as developers constantlt refactor or restructure it so it changes time to time. So better you can ask them to add data-testid or id locators. These data-testid or ids will not change unless they change it deliberately
